Note:
Runa Standard Library: Statistics Utilities

Provides comprehensive statistical functions for analyzing data, including descriptive statistics, probability distributions, hypothesis testing, and advanced data analysis.

Idiomatic Runa code uses natural language operators:
  Let avg be mean of numbers
  Let med be median of numbers
  Let std_dev be standard deviation of numbers
  Let correlation be correlation between x_values and y_values

For advanced/AI-generated code, use helpers:
  Let result be calculate with data as values and statistic as "mean"
  Let result be test_hypothesis with data as values and test as "t_test"
:End Note

Process called "mean" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let total be 0
    For each x in data:
        Set total to total plus x
    Return total divided by length of data

Process called "median" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let sorted_data be sort(data)
    Let n be length of sorted_data
    If n modulo 2 is equal to 1:
        Return sorted_data at index n divided by 2
    Otherwise:
        Let mid1 be sorted_data at index (n divided by 2) minus 1
        Let mid2 be sorted_data at index n divided by 2
        Return (mid1 plus mid2) divided by 2

Process called "mode" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let counts be dictionary with
    For each x in data:
        If x in counts:
            Set counts[x] to counts[x] plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Set counts[x] to 1
    Let max_count be 0
    Let mode_value be None
    For each key and value in counts:
        If value is greater than max_count:
            Set max_count to value
            Set mode_value to key
    Return mode_value

Process called "variance" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let avg be mean of data
    Let total be 0
    For each x in data:
        Set total to total plus (x minus avg) to the power of 2
    Return total divided by length of data

Process called "stdev" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Return square root of variance of data

Process called "sample_variance" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let avg be mean of data
    Let total be 0
    For each x in data:
        Set total to total plus (x minus avg) to the power of 2
    Return total divided by (length of data minus 1)

Process called "sample_stdev" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Return square root of sample variance of data

Process called "geometric_mean" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let product be 1
    For each x in data:
        Set product to product times x
    Return product to the power of (1 divided by length of data)

Process called "harmonic_mean" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let sum_reciprocals be 0
    For each x in data:
        Set sum_reciprocals to sum_reciprocals plus (1 divided by x)
    Return length of data divided by sum_reciprocals

Process called "weighted_mean" that takes data as List[Number] and weights as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let weighted_sum be 0
    Let weight_sum be 0
    For each i in range from 0 to length of data:
        Set weighted_sum to weighted_sum plus (data[i] times weights[i])
        Set weight_sum to weight_sum plus weights[i]
    Return weighted_sum divided by weight_sum

Process called "trimmed_mean" that takes data as List[Number] and proportion as Number returns Number:
    Let sorted_data be sort(data)
    Let n be length of sorted_data
    Let trim_count be floor(n times proportion)
    Let trimmed_data be slice of sorted_data from trim_count to n minus trim_count
    Return mean of trimmed_data

Process called "winsorized_mean" that takes data as List[Number] and proportion as Number returns Number:
    Let sorted_data be sort(data)
    Let n be length of sorted_data
    Let trim_count be floor(n times proportion)
    Let winsorized_data be copy of sorted_data
    For each i in range from 0 to trim_count:
        Set winsorized_data[i] to sorted_data[trim_count]
        Set winsorized_data[n minus 1 minus i] to sorted_data[n minus 1 minus trim_count]
    Return mean of winsorized_data

Process called "percentile" that takes data as List[Number] and p as Number returns Number:
    Let sorted_data be sort(data)
    Let n be length of sorted_data
    Let index be (p divided by 100) times (n minus 1)
    Let lower_index be floor(index)
    Let upper_index be ceiling(index)
    If lower_index is equal to upper_index:
        Return sorted_data[lower_index]
    Otherwise:
        Let weight be index minus lower_index
        Return (1 minus weight) times sorted_data[lower_index] plus weight times sorted_data[upper_index]

Process called "quartiles" that takes data as List[Number] returns List[Number]:
    Let q1 be percentile of data at 25
    Let q2 be percentile of data at 50
    Let q3 be percentile of data at 75
    Return [q1, q2, q3]

Process called "iqr" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let qs be quartiles of data
    Return qs[2] minus qs[0]

Process called "skewness" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let avg be mean of data
    Let std be stdev of data
    Let n be length of data
    Let sum_cubed be 0
    For each x in data:
        Set sum_cubed to sum_cubed plus ((x minus avg) divided by std) to the power of 3
    Return (n times sum_cubed) divided by ((n minus 1) times (n minus 2))

Process called "kurtosis" that takes data as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let avg be mean of data
    Let std be stdev of data
    Let n be length of data
    Let sum_fourth be 0
    For each x in data:
        Set sum_fourth to sum_fourth plus ((x minus avg) divided by std) to the power of 4
    Return ((n times (n plus 1) times sum_fourth) divided by ((n minus 1) times (n minus 2) times (n minus 3))) minus (3 times (n minus 1) times (n minus 1) divided by ((n minus 2) times (n minus 3)))

Process called "covariance" that takes x as List[Number] and y as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let x_mean be mean of x
    Let y_mean be mean of y
    Let n be length of x
    Let sum_product be 0
    For each i in range from 0 to n:
        Set sum_product to sum_product plus ((x[i] minus x_mean) times (y[i] minus y_mean))
    Return sum_product divided by n

Process called "correlation" that takes x as List[Number] and y as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let cov be covariance of x and y
    Let x_std be stdev of x
    Let y_std be stdev of y
    Return cov divided by (x_std times y_std)

Process called "rank_correlation" that takes x as List[Number] and y as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let x_ranks be rank data x
    Let y_ranks be rank data y
    Return correlation of x_ranks and y_ranks

Process called "rank_data" that takes data as List[Number] returns List[Integer]:
    Let sorted_data be sort(data)
    Let ranks be list with length of data
    For each i in range from 0 to length of data:
        Let rank be index of data[i] in sorted_data
        Set ranks[i] to rank plus 1
    Return ranks

Process called "z_score" that takes data as List[Number] returns List[Number]:
    Let avg be mean of data
    Let std be stdev of data
    Let z_scores be list with length of data
    For each i in range from 0 to length of data:
        Set z_scores[i] to (data[i] minus avg) divided by std
    Return z_scores

Process called "normalize" that takes data as List[Number] returns List[Number]:
    Let min_val be minimum of data
    Let max_val be maximum of data
    Let range_val be max_val minus min_val
    Let normalized be list with length of data
    For each i in range from 0 to length of data:
        Set normalized[i] to (data[i] minus min_val) divided by range_val
    Return normalized

Process called "standardize" that takes data as List[Number] returns List[Number]:
    Return z_score of data

Process called "outliers" that takes data as List[Number] and method as String returns List[Number]:
    If method is equal to "iqr":
        Let qs be quartiles of data
        Let iqr_val be qs[2] minus qs[0]
        Let lower_bound be qs[0] minus (1.5 times iqr_val)
        Let upper_bound be qs[2] plus (1.5 times iqr_val)
        Let outlier_list be list with
        For each x in data:
            If x is less than lower_bound or x is greater than upper_bound:
                Add x to outlier_list
        Return outlier_list
    Otherwise if method is equal to "zscore":
        Let z_scores be z_score of data
        Let outlier_list be list with
        For each i in range from 0 to length of data:
            If absolute value of z_scores[i] is greater than 3:
                Add data[i] to outlier_list
        Return outlier_list
    Otherwise:
        Return empty list

Process called "frequency_table" that takes data as List[Number] returns Dictionary[Number, Integer]:
    Let freq_table be dictionary with
    For each x in data:
        If x in freq_table:
            Set freq_table[x] to freq_table[x] plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Set freq_table[x] to 1
    Return freq_table

Process called "relative_frequency" that takes data as List[Number] returns Dictionary[Number, Number]:
    Let freq_table be frequency table of data
    Let n be length of data
    Let rel_freq be dictionary with
    For each key and value in freq_table:
        Set rel_freq[key] to value divided by n
    Return rel_freq

Process called "cumulative_frequency" that takes data as List[Number] returns Dictionary[Number, Number]:
    Let freq_table be frequency table of data
    Let sorted_keys be sort keys of freq_table
    Let cum_freq be dictionary with
    Let running_total be 0
    For each key in sorted_keys:
        Set running_total to running_total plus freq_table[key]
        Set cum_freq[key] to running_total
    Return cum_freq

Process called "confidence_interval" that takes data as List[Number] and confidence as Number returns List[Number]:
    Let n be length of data
    Let mean_val be mean of data
    Let std_err be sample stdev of data divided by square root of n
    Let z_critical be 1.96  Note: For 95% confidence
    If confidence is equal to 0.99:
        Set z_critical to 2.576
    Otherwise if confidence is equal to 0.90:
        Set z_critical to 1.645
    Let margin be z_critical times std_err
    Return [mean_val minus margin, mean_val plus margin]

Process called "t_test" that takes data1 as List[Number] and data2 as List[Number] returns Dictionary[String, Number]:
    Let n1 be length of data1
    Let n2 be length of data2
    Let mean1 be mean of data1
    Let mean2 be mean of data2
    Let var1 be sample variance of data1
    Let var2 be sample variance of data2
    
    Let pooled_var be ((n1 minus 1) times var1 plus (n2 minus 1) times var2) divided by (n1 plus n2 minus 2)
    Let t_stat be (mean1 minus mean2) divided by square root of (pooled_var times (1 divided by n1 plus 1 divided by n2))
    Let df be n1 plus n2 minus 2
    
    Return dictionary with "t_statistic" as t_stat and "degrees_of_freedom" as df

Process called "chi_square_test" that takes observed as List[Number] and expected as List[Number] returns Dictionary[String, Number]:
    Let chi_square be 0
    For each i in range from 0 to length of observed:
        Let diff be observed[i] minus expected[i]
        Set chi_square to chi_square plus (diff times diff) divided by expected[i]
    Let df be length of observed minus 1
    Return dictionary with "chi_square" as chi_square and "degrees_of_freedom" as df

Process called "anova" that takes groups as List[List[Number]] returns Dictionary[String, Number]:
    Let k be length of groups
    Let total_n be 0
    Let grand_mean be 0
    Let total_sum be 0
    
    For each group in groups:
        Let n be length of group
        Set total_n to total_n plus n
        For each x in group:
            Set total_sum to total_sum plus x
    
    Set grand_mean to total_sum divided by total_n
    
    Let ss_between be 0
    Let ss_within be 0
    
    For each group in groups:
        Let group_mean be mean of group
        Let n be length of group
        Set ss_between to ss_between plus (n times (group_mean minus grand_mean) times (group_mean minus grand_mean))
        For each x in group:
            Set ss_within to ss_within plus (x minus group_mean) times (x minus group_mean)
    
    Let df_between be k minus 1
    Let df_within be total_n minus k
    Let ms_between be ss_between divided by df_between
    Let ms_within be ss_within divided by df_within
    Let f_stat be ms_between divided by ms_within
    
    Return dictionary with "f_statistic" as f_stat and "df_between" as df_between and "df_within" as df_within

Process called "linear_regression" that takes x as List[Number] and y as List[Number] returns Dictionary[String, Number]:
    Let n be length of x
    Let x_mean be mean of x
    Let y_mean be mean of y
    
    Let numerator be 0
    Let denominator be 0
    
    For each i in range from 0 to n:
        Set numerator to numerator plus ((x[i] minus x_mean) times (y[i] minus y_mean))
        Set denominator to denominator plus ((x[i] minus x_mean) times (x[i] minus x_mean))
    
    Let slope be numerator divided by denominator
    Let intercept be y_mean minus (slope times x_mean)
    
    Let ss_res be 0
    Let ss_tot be 0
    
    For each i in range from 0 to n:
        Let y_pred be intercept plus (slope times x[i])
        Set ss_res to ss_res plus (y[i] minus y_pred) times (y[i] minus y_pred)
        Set ss_tot to ss_tot plus (y[i] minus y_mean) times (y[i] minus y_mean)
    
    Let r_squared be 1 minus (ss_res divided by ss_tot)
    
    Return dictionary with "slope" as slope and "intercept" as intercept and "r_squared" as r_squared

Process called "predict" that takes model as Dictionary[String, Number] and x as Number returns Number:
    Let slope be model["slope"]
    Let intercept be model["intercept"]
    Return intercept plus (slope times x)

Process called "residuals" that takes x as List[Number] and y as List[Number] and model as Dictionary[String, Number] returns List[Number]:
    Let residuals be list with length of x
    For each i in range from 0 to length of x):
        Let y_pred be predict with model as model and x as x[i]
        Set residuals[i] to y[i] minus y_pred
    Return residuals

Process called "mae" that takes actual as List[Number] and predicted as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let total_error be 0
    For each i in range from 0 to length of actual:
        Set total_error to total_error plus absolute value of (actual[i] minus predicted[i])
    Return total_error divided by length of actual

Process called "mse" that takes actual as List[Number] and predicted as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let total_error be 0
    For each i in range from 0 to length of actual:
        Set total_error to total_error plus (actual[i] minus predicted[i]) times (actual[i] minus predicted[i])
    Return total_error divided by length of actual

Process called "rmse" that takes actual as List[Number] and predicted as List[Number] returns Number:
    Return square root of mse of actual and predicted

Process called "mape" that takes actual as List[Number] and predicted as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let total_error be 0
    For each i in range from 0 to length of actual:
        If actual[i] is not equal to 0:
            Set total_error to total_error plus absolute value of ((actual[i] minus predicted[i]) divided by actual[i])
    Return (total_error divided by length of actual) times 100

Process called "r2_score" that takes actual as List[Number] and predicted as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let actual_mean be mean of actual
    Let ss_res be 0
    Let ss_tot be 0
    
    For each i in range from 0 to length of actual:
        Set ss_res to ss_res plus (actual[i] minus predicted[i]) times (actual[i] minus predicted[i])
        Set ss_tot to ss_tot plus (actual[i] minus actual_mean) times (actual[i] minus actual_mean)
    
    Return 1 minus (ss_res divided by ss_tot) 